stemic shift, which he calls "border thinking." Further, he expands the horizons of those debates already under way in postcolonial studies of Asia and Africa by dwelling in the genealogy of thoughts of South/Central America, the Caribbean, and Latino/as in the United States. His concept of "border gnosis," or sensing and knowing by dwelling in imperial/colonial borderlands, counters the tendency of occidentalist perspectives to manage, and thus limit, understanding. In a new preface that discusses Local Histories/Global Designs as a dialogue with Hegel's Philosophy of History, Mignolo connects his argument with the unfolding of history in the first decade of the twenty-first century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aColonies. 0aCulture. 0aHermeneutics. 0aHistoryxPhilosophy. 0aKnowledge, Theory ofxPolitical aspects. 0aPostcolonialism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aCaribbean.  aCentral America.  aCrolization.  aEurocentrism.  aFlorencia Mallon.  aHaitian Revolution.  aLatin America.  aLatin American Subaltern Studies Group.  aMaghreb.  aOccidentalism.  aOrientalism.  aSouth America.  aSouth Asian subaltern studies.  aanthropologians.  aanthropologists.  aarea studies.  aborder thinking.  acivilization borders.  acivilizing process.  acoevalness.  acolonial India.  acolonial borderland.  acolonial difference.  acolonial epistemic difference.  acolonial histories.  acommunity formation.  acultural production.  acultural revolutions.  aculture.  adeconstruction.  adisarticulations.  aepistemic colonial difference.  ageohistorical locations.  ageopolitical configurations.  ageopolitical values.  ageopolitics.  aglobal designs.  ahegemonic knowledges.  ahierarchical structures.  aidentification.  aimperial bo